ICE Arrest at Salt Lake Airport Sparks City Backlash Federal agents arrested 39-year-old Marta Brizeyda Renderos Leiva at Salt Lake City International Airport on Oct. 29. According to ICE, Renderos Leiva is an illegal immigrant from El Salvador who entered the U.S. in 2007 and was ordered removed in 2020. Officials say she was taken into custody during a targeted enforcement operation and is being held pending removal. The arrest, made by Homeland Security and Border Patrol agents acting on ICE’s behalf, happened near the airport’s baggage claim area. The Salt Lake City Council called the operation “unusual” and said it “creates fear and uncertainty in our community,” emphasizing it was not coordinated with city police. The council says it’s seeking more information from federal authorities. Mayor Erin Mendenhall also condemned the incident, saying she reviewed footage of plain-clothed agents detaining the woman in a public area of the terminal. “Nothing about this incident, like so many ICE operations, makes me feel safer as an American,” she said. Both the mayor and city council reiterated that the Salt Lake City Police Department had no role in the operation and is prohibited by federal law from interfering with immigration enforcement. Video by Shanon Hale

A Milestone for Our Planet! At #IUCNWCC last week, Resolution 007 towards a Soil Security Law was officially adopted — a historic step recognizing that healthy, living soil is the foundation of well-being for all Life on Earth. Initiated, sponsored, and tabled by SoilSAL, Save Soil, and GCELS, this #IUCNResolution 007 is now our collective call to action. We can’t safeguard our future without safeguarding the soil beneath our feet. From supporting biodiversity preservation to climate change mitigation and adaptation, and ensuring food, water, and energy security, soil is at the heart of our planet’s health — and now, it’s one stride closer to getting the legal protection it deserves. Why it matters: ● Global recognition for urgent, comprehensive, legal protection for soil  ● Jumpstarts multi-stakeholder collaboration to develop concepts and parameters for an international convention or a global legal instrument on soil security ● Aligns fragmented global mechanisms and promotes policy coherence across local, national, regional, and international governance levels to scale soil as a nexus solution for global existential challenges ● Recognizes Indigenous peoples’ roles in soil stewardship and sustainable agriculture to revitalize soil In the words of the late Dr. Jane Goodall: “We know what we must do, so Let’s Make It Happen!” @iucn_wcel
 

#SaveSoil

NEW: NYC Mayor-elect Zohran Mamdani challenges President Trump in his victory speech: “New York will remain a city of immigrants, a city built by immigrants, powered by immigrants. And as of tonight, led by an immigrant.” “So hear me, President Trump, when I say this: To get any of us, you will have to get through all of us.”

Zohran Mamdani told Donald Trump to "turn the volume up" as he addressed his supporters during a victory speech after he won New York City's mayoral race, saying that the city that made the president is also the city that can show the country how to defeat him. "We will refuse to allow those who traffic in division and hate to pit us against one another," Mamdani told supporters on Tuesday. "In this moment of darkness, New York will be the light. We believe in standing up for those we love, whether you are an immigrant, a member of the trans community, any Black women that Donald Trump has fired from a federal job." Speaking directly to the president, Mamdani then said, "Donald Trump, since I know you're watching, I have four words for you: Turn the volume up." Mamdani, 34, who is a self-described democratic socialist, will be the city’s youngest mayor in over a century. He will also be New York City's first Muslim mayor and person of South Asian descent to hold the role. He defeated former Gov. Andrew Cuomo, who ran as an independent, and Republican Curtis Sliwa.

🇮🇹🔴Italian victim's family reacted with rage after Nigerian migrant Khalid De Greata was sentenced to only 12 years in prison due to "boat stress" from his journey to Italy over the Mediterranean. "In 12 years, I'll kill him," said the son of the victim after the verdict, which was issued in 2019. The Nigerian slit the throat of 51-year-old Maurizio Gugliotta in a market in Turin, leaving the beloved father to bleed to death on the street. "It's a disgrace, you're heartless," shouted Gugliotta's relatives when the verdict was read out. The judge issued the Nigerian a reduced sentence, which was upheld by the Italian Supreme Court in 2019, because he was a migrant and had "boat stress" from his journey to Italy. The family did not buy the diagnosis. "I wonder why when he entered Italy they didn't notice, didn't check him in all these months during which he roamed around our country. Is it possible that they only discover he was crazy after he killed a man?" said Gugliotta's widow at the time. The case dated back to Oct. 17, 2017. The Nigerian slashed Maurizio Gugliotta in the throat for no reason. Gugliotta fled the Turin market after being stabbed, only to die on the street after bleeding out. The Nigerian man was found by police shortly afterwards smoking a cigarette and calmly wiping blood from his knife.
